  • Either sporadic or autosomal dominant

" In February of 2015, after a busy weekend, I began feeling some tingling in the bottom of my feet. I thought that I was just sore from wearing heels, but within a few days, the numbness and tingling proceeded to go up my shins and into my knees and through my thighs"
Source

  • chronic T cell-mediated autoimmune disorder characterised by demyelination in the central nervous system with multiple plaques of demyelination found throughout the brain and spinal cord
  • Peripheral myelinated nerves are NOT affected.
  • 3 times more common in women
  • most commonly diagnosed in people aged 20-40 years
  • Relapsing remitting disease is the most common form with acute attacks lasting 1-2 months with remissions.
    • Relapses are caused by acute inflammation causing myelin damage and conduction block.
  • around 65% of patients with relapsing-remitting disease go on to develop secondary progressive disease within 15 years of diagnosis.
    • That means -> development of permanent neurologic deficits:
    • gait and bladder disorders are generally seen
  • Primary progressive disease is commoner in older people
  • Demyelination has a prediliction of cervical spinal cord, optic nerves, corpus callosum, cerebellar connections of the brainstem. (contrast with PML where spinal cord and optic nerves are spared)

Symptoms:

  • Paraesthesia is an early complaint.
  • Spasticity
  • Autonomic: bladder / bowel and sexual dysfunction.
  • Cerebellar: charcot triad -> Scanning speech, nystagmus and intention tremmor.
  • [[Ophthalmologic diseases#Optic neuritis|Optic neuritis]] : (classic presentation -> unilateral, moderate, painful vision loss with afferent pupillary defect and normal fundus examination.
  • Depression
  • [[General medicine 6-Neurology#Trigeminal neuralgia|Trigeminal Neuralgia]]

Investigations:

  • MRI
  • CSF - "oligoclonal bands" and intrathecal IgG production.
  • Evoked potentials - Non specific.

Management:

  • No cure
  • Symptomatic treatment for various system involvement.
    • Incontinence: USS is essential to assess residual bladder volume to exclude overflow incontinence as oxybutinin may worsen symptoms if prescribed before USS assessment)
  • Disease modifying drugs:
    • natalizumab - monoclonal antibody which inhibits leukocyte migration across the blood brain barrier. - IV
    • ocrelizumab - IV
    • Fingolimod - sphongosine receptor modulator
    • Two older drugs
      • beta interferon - considered to be not as efective.
      • glatiramer acetate - immune decoy - reduced relapse frequency and reduce development of new MRI lesions. Given Sub cut or IM.
    • Oral disease modifying drugs are also available.

Haemostasis

  1. The quickest response to endothelial damage is formation of the platelet plug. Platelets roll off the exposed collagen and stick to it.

[!INFO] Platelet activation and aggregation

Adhesion, activation and aggregation. (A) Endothelial injury in the blood vessel exposes collagen to platelets and von Willebrand factors (vWF). (B) Resting platelets attach to the exposed collagen with their glycoprotein surface receptors directly and/or via vWF mediated anchorage. (C) The platelet, upon adhesion to collagen, is activated, changes morphology and releases granular contents which activate more platelets. Activated platelets induce conformational change in a surface receptor, namely, glycoprotein receptor (GP)IIb/IIIa, which induces (D) platelet aggregation via vWF and fibrinogen. (E) Aggregated platelets form a plug at the site of the injury, thereby stopping the blood leakage temporarily. ADP: Adenosine diphosphate; TxA 2 : Thromboxane A 2 ; vWF: von Willebrand factor; GP: glycoprotein receptors. (Figure courtesy of biorender.com).

[!INFO] How to visualize what platelet 'aggregation' means
Prostaglandins influence intra platelet calcium via cAMP;
Ca2+ is required for the processes which produce platelet aggregation and adhesion.

  • prostacylin reduces platelet calcium.
  • Thromboxane increases platelet calcium.

Coagulation cascade and assessment

[!INFO] What is Tissue factor?
AKA Factor III, aka Tissue thromboplastin.
Tissue factor (TF) is best known as the primary cellular initiator of blood coagulation. It is a transmembrane protein.
After vessel injury, the TF:FVIIa complex activates the coagulation protease cascade, which leads to fibrin deposition and activation of platelets Source
Aberrant TF expression triggers intravascular thrombosis associated with various diseases, such as atherosclerosis, cancer, and sepsis

Fibrinolytic system and drugs

John Cunningham virus and PML

The evaluation of new-onset neurological symptoms in a patient with suspected or confirmed immunosuppression should include progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy as part of the differential diagnosis.

Source

Usually harmless but in immunocompromised states it can cause progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy.
Reactivation causes PML.
PML affects oligodendrocytes and causes demyelination

Signs of PML:

  • progressive, multifocal, subacute focal neurological deficits that vary depending on the site of the lesion and include a spectrum of presentations including cognitive impairment, limb ataxia, gait ataxia, hemiparesis, hemianopia, and aphasia
  • Optic nerve and Spinal cord are usually spared.

T lymphocytes play a major role in the normal immune response to JC virus.
PML is rare but fatal is most cases.
JC is a DNA virus.

No specific treatment identified.
But in AIDS patients, prompt initiation of HAART is advised.


Treatment: Goal is only to prolong survival.

  • Anticholinergics: Oxybutinin (smooth muscle antispasmodic), similar mechanism to tolterodine
    • Tolterodine - selective M3 antagonist.
    • Oxybutinin - non selective muscarinic antagonis.
  • more drugs - Source
  • for stress incontinence, the treatment is to increase contractility if the skeletally smooth muscle if the urethral sphincter. Duloxetine (centrally acting SNRI) can be used.

Source

Optic neuritis

Impairment of visual acuity over hours to days with occular pain (worsening with eye movement) and loss of colour vision out of proportion to loss of acuity.

Loss of colour vision > loss of acuity = specific to optic nerve pathology

  • Afferent pupilary defect always occurs.
  • Visual defect is a central scotoma
  • Commoner in females around 20 - 40 years old.
  • Strongly associated with development of multiple sclerosis.
  • Optic neuritis associated vision loss is a presenting complaint in about 20% of MS. Stronger association with MS if MRI shows "two or more white matter lesions"
    Pathogenesis: Commonest is inflamatory demyelinition of the optic nerve.
  • Low dose aspirin irreversibly inhibits COX-1(and also COX-2) -> inhibits Thromboxane A2 production. See [[Coagulation#^818075|prostacyclin]]
  • Clopidogrel (which is a prodrug) and prasugrel irreversibly inhibit the binding of adenosine to P2Y12 receptors
  • Ticagrelor produces non-competitive reversible inhibition.
  • They inhibit adenosine mediated platelet aggregation.
  • Clopidogrel is the prodrug. It's activated by the CYP2C19 enzyme system which can be inhibited by omeprazole!. Don't co administer the drugs.
  • Prasugrel -> rash and angiooedema rarely.
    • Prasugrel is not used after ischemic stroke / TIA due to increased bleeding risk.
  • 📑Abciximab is a monoclonal antibody which does this;** Only one dose can be given** before the body forms effective antibodies to it.
  • 📑Tirofiban and eptifibatide are also IIb/IIIa blockers which are given IV to reduce early events in ACS.

Transverse myelitis

Transverse myelitis (TM) is a rare, acquired focal inflammatory disorder of the spinal cord often presenting with rapid onset weakness, sensory deficits, and bowel/bladder dysfunction.

perivascular infiltration, demyelination, and axonal injury by monocytes and lymphocytes at the lesion site. (Gray and white matter is involved so it's not purely demyelinating).

  • Most common cause is idiopathic
  • Infections leading to TM include, but are not limited to, enteroviruses, West Nile virus, herpes viruses, HIV, human T-cell leukemia virus type 1 (HTLV-1), Zika virus, neuroborreliosis (Lyme), Mycoplasma, and Treponema pallidum
- These medications function by **inhibiting serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake within the presynaptic terminals**, resulting in elevated concentrations of these neurotransmitters within the synaptic cleft

Management of pneumothorax

  • New British Thoracic Society guidelines emphasise symptom-guided management.
    • no or minimal symptoms → conservative care, regardless of pneumothorax size
    • symptomatic → assess for high-risk characteristics
      • High risk characteristics:
          • haemodynamic compromise (suggesting a tension pneumothorax)
        • significant hypoxia
        • bilateral pneumothorax
        • underlying lung disease
        • ≥ 50 years of age with significant smoking history
        • haemothorax
      • If High risk characteristics are present -> IC tube.
      • If no high risk characteristics -> choice of conservative / ambulatory device / needle aspiration.
